<Base title="OSfile (.primefile) — ostk governance" description="The kernel identity document. Written by the OS, not by you. Records the running kernel version and signing authority.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>OSfile <span style="font-weight: normal; color: var(--color-muted)">(.primefile)</span></h1>
    <p class="lead">The kernel's identity document. The OS writes it. You read it to verify what's running.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      The OSfile (<code>.haystack/.primefile</code>) is the kernel identity document —
      the OS's equivalent of your HUMANFILE. You don't write it. The kernel writes and
      signs it at initialization, and updates it on version changes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Read it to understand what kernel version is running, who signed it, and
      what the active trust chain looks like.
    </p>

    <h2>Location</h2>
    <p><code>.haystack/.primefile</code> — in your project's haystack state directory.</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code># .primefile — haystack kernel identity

## Kernel
- name: haystack
- version: 1.0.2
- identity_counter: 934
- boot_protocol: fcp-haystack
- audit_backend: jsonl

## Paths
- needles: .haystack/needles/
- audit: .haystack/audit.jsonl
- boot: .haystack/boot.md
- human: .haystack/HUMANFILE
- agents: .haystack/agents.jsonl

## Session
- last_agent: agent-934
- last_session: 2026-03-12T19:00:00Z
- last_needle: →648

## Signing
- root_key: 99B076C9        # kernel root GPG key
- ci_key: 6893C46C          # CI signing key, subordinate to root</code></pre>

    <h2>Fields</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>version</code></td><td>Running kernel version. Compare to latest release to check for updates.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>identity_counter</code></td><td>Monotonically increasing agent identity counter. Resets only on fresh init.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>boot_protocol</code></td><td>Which boot protocol is active. <code>fcp-haystack</code> = tack-aware boot.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>audit_backend</code></td><td>How the audit trail is stored. <code>jsonl</code> = append-only JSONL.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>last_session</code></td><td>ISO timestamp of the last clean shutdown.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>root_key</code></td><td>GPG fingerprint of the kernel root signing key.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Signature verification</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>.primefile</code> is GPG-signed by the kernel root key. To verify the
      running kernel hasn't been tampered with:
    </p>
    <pre><code>gpg --verify .haystack/.primefile.asc .haystack/.primefile</code></pre>
    <p>
      If verification fails, the kernel should not be trusted. The signature chain runs:
      human T0 key → kernel root key → CI key. Each link in the chain is cross-signed.
    </p>

    <h2>You don't edit this</h2>
    <p>
      Unlike HUMANFILE and ENTITYFILE, you do not write the OSfile. The kernel owns it.
      Modifying it manually will invalidate the signature and may cause the kernel to
      refuse to boot. If you need to update kernel configuration, use the provided
      governance commands rather than direct edits.
    </p>

